'''Fantasy Congress''' was an online [[fantasy sport|fantasy simulation sport]] where players, called citizens, could draft members of the [[United States Congress|United States House and Senate]], and keep track of their participation within the U.S. Congress. Actions, especially within the process of making and amending pieces of [[legislation]], of a player's drafted congresspersons were recorded and rated as a cumulative total amount of points against other players.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.nytimes.com/2006/10/23/washington/23fantasy.html | title=Fantasy Sports? Childâ€™s Play. Here, Politics Is the Game. | publisher=[[Arthur Ochs Sulzberger, Jr.]] | work=[[The New York Times]] | date=October 23, 2006 | accessdate=June 28, 2011 | author=Chang, Cindy | location=[[Washington, DC]] | archiveurl=http://liveweb.archive.org/http://www.nytimes.com/2006/10/23/washington/23fantasy.html?_r=3 | archivedate=February 19, 2009}}</ref>
Fantasy Congress, which ran from 2006 to 2009, was meant to appeal to both recreational and educational players; it offered a wide range of links and research tools to help players in choosing their members of Congress whose activity their scores will derive from. The creators explained that the game could even work to make the government more accountable.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.escapistmagazine.com/articles/view/issues/issue_121/2572-Fantasy-Congress | title=Fantasy Congress | work=''[[The Escapist (website)|The Escapist]]'' | date=October 30, 2007 | accessdate=June 28, 2011 | author=Blancato, Joe | archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/5wChwPAKS | archivedate=February 2, 2011}}</ref>
== History == The premise of Fantasy Congress was originally developed by students at [[Claremont McKenna College]] in [[Claremont, California|Claremont]], [[California]].<ref>{{cite news | url=http://abcnews.go.com/Politics/story?id=2602470&page=1 | title=Video Games, Internet Sites Going Political | work=''[[ABC News]]'' | date=October 24, 2006 | accessdate=June 28, 2011 | author=Venkataraman, Nitya}}</ref> They came up with an idea for a game that would blend the trading and other gameplay of popular fantasy sports games with politics.<ref>{{cite web|title=History of Fantasy Congress|publisher=Fantasy Congress|accessdate=June 28, 2011|archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20071025062745/http://www.fantasycongress.com/public/History.jsp|archivedate=October 25, 2007}}</ref>
== Gameplay == Points within Fantasy Congress were calculated based on "Legislative success" (including co-sponsored legislation and amendments),<ref>{{cite web|title=How Do I Play?|publisher=Fantasy Congress|accessdate=June 28, 2011|archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20071030140207/http://www.fantasycongress.com/public/HowDoIPlay.jsp|archivedate=October 30, 2007}}</ref> voting attendance, "Maverick Score" (the willingness of a member of Congress to cross party lines in close party votes), and noteworthy news mentions. Legislative success is the progress of a congressperson's sponsored or cosponsored legislation through the U.S. legislative process, all the way up to the President's signature or veto. Also, small legislative actions counted for points, such as amendments and changes to the legislation.
